text:
[ PAGE 1 START ] Protective PolicingOverviewProtective Policing business line ispart of Federal Services provided bythe RCMP.  In the 1950s and 1960s RCMP members were assigned toCanadian dignitaries and major visitsfor ceremonial presence as well as forsecurity. It is only in the 1970s that ProtectivePolicing was established as anindependent  identifiable functionwithin the RCMP.Protection is extended to Canadian andforeign dignitaries  persons designatedby the Minister of Public Safety  majorevents held in Canada  and Canadianair carriers.Canadian DignitariesThe RCMP is mandated at all times during both private and officialfunctions  for the personal protectionof the Governor General of Canada the Prime Minister  their families andresidences. When traveling abroad  theGovernor General and the PrimeMinister are accompanied byProtective Policing members. Thesemembers maintain communicationwith local protective and lawenforcement authorities  ensuring thatappropriate levels of protection areprovided. The security measures implementedare commensurate with the high profilepositions held by the GovernorGeneral as the representative of theHead of State and of the PrimeMinister as the Head of Government.The RCMP continuously assesses thesecurity requirements  and as a matterof practice makes recommendations tothe Governor General and PrimeMinister with respect to the effectivedelivery of security measures  whichwould include advice regardingtransportation. For security and safetyreasons  the RCMP requests that alltheir air movements be on governmentaircraft. Protective Policing is responsible forthe safety of Supreme and FederalCourt judges  as well as FederalCabinet Ministers.  Protective Policingalso secure designated protected sites including the grounds of ParliamentHill  Rideau Hall  and the SupremeCourt of Canada. It also has a TrafficUnit that is responsible for enforcingprovincial and federal traffic acts onNational Capital Commissionroadways in the National CapitalRegion.Foreign DignitariesInternationally Protected Persons  suchas Heads of State and government andforeign diplomats  are provided withprotection while in Canada.Major EventsSecurity at significant national orQuick FactsRCMP ProtectivePolicing is responsiblefor:\xc5\x81
Over 125 embassiesand highcommissions in theNational CapitalRegion;\xc5\x81
The protection of 500Resident ForeignDiplomatic Missions;\xc5\x81
Approximately 500foreign Consulatesacross Canada; \xc5\x81
The security ofapproximately 500visits by foreigndignitaries andInternationallyProtected Persons peryear; \xc5\x81
Responding toapproximately 600demonstrations ayear on average; and\xc5\x81
Providing speciallytrained policeofficers on boardselect Canadianregistered aircraft.'[ PAGE 1 END ][ PAGE 2 START ] Protective Policinginternational events hosted by theFederal Government  including RoyalVisits and international summits fallunder the mandate of ProtectivePolicing.  Additionally  certain eventscan be designated to receive RCMPsecurity  such as the Olympic andParalympic Games.Air TravelIn 2001  as a result of an initiative putforward by Transport Canada  theRCMP entered into an agreement withCanadian Air Transport SecurityAuthority (CATSA) to providespecially-trained RCMP police officerson board select Canadian registeredaircraft.Protective Policing is responsible forthe training and deployment of tacticalAircraft Protective Officers (APOs) forselected domestic and internationalflights.  These APOs have a mandateto respond to security threats on boardselect Canadian registered aircraft.'[ PAGE 2 END ]

text: [ PAGE 1 START ] Police de protectionAper\xc3\xa7uLe secteur d\xe2\x84\xa2activit\xc3\xa9 de la Police deprotection fait partie des Servicesf\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9raux offerts par la GRC. Dans lesann\xc3\xa9es 1950 et 1960  des membres dela GRC \xc3\xa9taient affect\xc3\xa9s aux visitesmajeures et aux visites de dignitairescanadiens \xc3\xa0 des fins c\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9moniales et des\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9.  Ce n\xe2\x84\xa2est que dans les ann\xc3\xa9es 1970qu\xe2\x84\xa2on a \xc3\xa9tabli la Police de protectioncomme une fonction ind\xc3\xa9pendante etdistincte au sein de la GRC.Cette protection s\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9tend aux dignitairescanadiens et \xc3\xa9trangers ainsi qu\xe2\x84\xa2auxpersonnes d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9es par le ministre dela S\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 publique. Elle couvre\xc3\xa9galement les \xc3\xa9v\xc3\xa9nements majeurstenus au pays et les transporteursa\xc3\xa9riens canadiens.Dignitaires canadiensLa GRC a la responsabilit\xc3\xa9 en touttemps  \xc3\xa0 la fois durant les \xc3\xa9v\xc3\xa8nementspriv\xc3\xa9s et officiels  d\xe2\x84\xa2assurer laprotection de la gouverneure g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9raledu Canada  du premier ministre  et deleurs familles et r\xc3\xa9sidences. Lors deleurs d\xc3\xa9placements \xc3\xa0 l\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9tranger  lagouverneure g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9rale et le premierministre sont accompagn\xc3\xa9s par desmembres de la Police de protection.Ces membres restent encommunication avec les autorit\xc3\xa9spolici\xc3\xa8res et de protection locales etassurent une protection appropri\xc3\xa9e estre\xc3\xa7ue. Les mesures de s\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 offertescorrespondent \xc3\xa0 l\xe2\x84\xa2importance despostes occup\xc3\xa9s par Son Excellence entant que repr\xc3\xa9sentant du Chef d\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\x89tat etpar le premier ministre en tant queChef du gouvernement.La GRC \xc3\xa9value continuellement lesexigences au plan de la s\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 et faitdes recommandations \xc3\xa0 laGouverneure g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9rale et au premierministre quant \xc3\xa0 la prestation efficacedes mesures de s\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9  ce quienglobe l\xe2\x84\xa2offre de conseils en mati\xc3\xa8rede transport. Pour des raisons des\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 et de protection  la GRCdemande que ceux-ci effectuent tousleurs d\xc3\xa9placements en avion \xc3\xa0 bord del\xe2\x84\xa2a\xc3\xa9ronef du gouvernement.La Police de protection assure las\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 des juges de la Cour supr\xc3\xaameet des autres cours f\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9rales  ainsi quedes ministres du Cabinet f\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9ral. LaPolice de protection garde aussi dessites prot\xc3\xa9g\xc3\xa9s d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9s  dont lesterrains de la Colline du Parlement  lar\xc3\xa9sidence de la gouverneure g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9rale(Rideau Hall) et la Cour supr\xc3\xaame duCanada. La Police de protectioncomporte \xc3\xa9galement un Groupe de las\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 routi\xc3\xa8re qui est responsabled\xe2\x84\xa2appliquer les lois provinciales etf\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9rales du code de la route sur lesroutes g\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9es par la Commission de lacapitale nationale dans la r\xc3\xa9gion de laEn BrefResponsabilit\xc3\xa9s de laPolice de protection dela GRC :\xc5\x81 Plus de 125ambassades et hauts-commissariats dans lar\xc3\xa9gion de la capitalenationale\xc5\x81 500 missionsdiplomatiques \xc5\x81 Environ 500consulats dansl\xe2\x84\xa2ensemble du pays\xc5\x81 Environ 500 visitespar an de dignitaires\xc3\xa9trangers et depersonnes jouissantd\xe2\x84\xa2une protectioninternationale\xc5\x81 Quelque 600manifestations par anen moyenne\xc5\x81 Affectation depoliciers form\xc3\xa9s \xc3\xa0 bordde certains a\xc3\xa9ronefsimmatricul\xc3\xa9s auCanada'[ PAGE 1 END ][ PAGE 2 START ] Police de protectionCapitale nationale.Dignitaires \xc3\xa9trangersLes personnes jouissant d\xe2\x84\xa2uneprotection internationale  comme leschefs d\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\x89tat et de gouvernement et lesdiplomates \xc3\xa9trangers  sont prot\xc3\xa9g\xc3\xa9espendant leur s\xc3\xa9jour au Canada.\xc3\x89v\xc3\xa9nements majeurs La s\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 lors d\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9v\xc3\xa9nements majeursnationaux ou internationaux organis\xc3\xa9spar le gouvernement du Canada  dontles visites royales et les sommetsinternationaux  font partie du mandatde la Police de protection. En outre certains \xc3\xa9v\xc3\xa9nements comme les Jeuxolympiques et paralympiques peuvent\xc3\xaatre d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9s pour que leur s\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9soit assur\xc3\xa9e par la GRC.D\xc3\xa9placements a\xc3\xa9riensEn 2001  dans le cadre d\xe2\x84\xa2une initiativelanc\xc3\xa9e par Transports Canada  la GRCa conclu une entente avecl\xe2\x84\xa2Administration canadienne de las\xc3\xbbret\xc3\xa9 du transport a\xc3\xa9rien (ACSTA)visant \xc3\xa0 affecter des membres de laGRC sp\xc3\xa9cialement form\xc3\xa9s \xc3\xa0 bord decertains a\xc3\xa9ronefs immatricul\xc3\xa9s auCanada. La Police de protection est responsablede la formation d\xe2\x84\xa2agents tactiques de las\xc3\xbbret\xc3\xa9 a\xc3\xa9rienne (ASA) et de leuraffectation \xc3\xa0 certains vols int\xc3\xa9rieurs etinternationaux. Ces agents ont pourmandat d\xe2\x84\xa2intervenir en cas de menace\xc3\xa0 la s\xc3\xa9curit\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 bord des a\xc3\xa9ronefsimmatricul\xc3\xa9s au Canada d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9s.'[ PAGE 2 END ]

[ PAGE 1 START ]   FORENSIC SCIENCE
 AND
 IDENTIFICATION SERVICES
         201
8-03-06 Guide to the Victims Index and Voluntary Donors Index 
of the National DNA Data Bank
 of Canada
  Issued under the 
authority of
 The Officer in Charge  National DNA Data Bank of Canada
     
   '[ PAGE 1 END ][ PAGE 2 START ]  Guide to the Victims Index and Voluntary Donors Index 
of the National DNA Data Bank
 of Canada
   Version 
1.0
 Effective Date: 201
8-03-06 Page 
2 of 
7  TABLE OF 
CONTENT
S 1 GENERAL
 ....................................................................................................................................................... 3 2 BACKGROUND
 ............................................................................................................................................... 3 3 VOLUNTARY PART
ICIPATION
 ......................................................................................................................... 3 4 SAMPLE COLLECTION AN
D CONSENT
 ............................................................................................................ 4 5 THE PROCESSING OF BI
OLOGICAL SAMPLES
 .................................................................................................. 4 6 SUBMITTING DNA PROFI
LES TO THE NDDB
 ................................................................................................... 5 7 DNA PROFILES RECEIVE
D AT THE NDDB
......................................................................................................... 5 8 ENTRY AND COMPARISON
 OF DNA PROFILES
................................................................................................ 5 9 MATCH NOTIFICATION
 .................................................................................................................................. 6 10 WITHD
RAWAL AND EXPIRY OF 
DNA PROFILES
 .............................................................................................. 6 11 COMMITMENT TO PRIVAC
Y .......................................................................................................................... 7    '[ PAGE 2 END ][ PAGE 3 START ]  Guide to the Victims Index and Voluntary Donors Index 
of the National DNA Data Bank
 of Canada
   Version 
1.0
 Effective Date: 201
8-03-06 Page 
3 of 
7  1 GENERAL
 This guide contains general information regarding the collection and submission of biological samples 
from 
victims 
of 
crime 
and 
voluntary 
donors
  as well as
 the entry of the 
resulting 
DNA profiles into the 
National 
DNA Data Bank.
 2 BACK
GROUND
 The RCMP is the steward of the N
ational DNA Data Bank (N
DDB
) on behalf of the Government of 
Canada
. The NDDB 
operates 
for the benefit of the entire law enforcement community within Canada. 
In 
2014
  the Government of Canada 
amended 
the 
DNA Identification Act
 to establish 
five new 
DNA 
indexes
 in the NDDB
: the 
Victims Index (VI)  the 
Voluntary Donors Index (VDI)  the Missing Persons Index
 (MPI)
  
the 
Human Remains Index
 (HRI)
 and 
the 
Relatives of Missing Persons Index
 (RMI)
. The
 MPI  HRI and RMI 
were created for 
the 
humanitarian purposes
 of investigating missing persons and human 
remains
 (refer 
to 
the 
Investigator\xe2\x84\xa2s Guide to the National Missing Persons DNA Program
). The 
VI may be 
used 
in the 
investigation of designated criminal 
offences
  and the 
VDI may be 
used 
to assist 
in 
both criminal and 
humanitarian investigations.
  
The 
VI contains DNA profiles from victim
s of designated offence
s who have 
voluntarily provided 
biological sample
s for the purpose of having their DNA profile add
ed to the 
VI. 
If victim
s of designated 
offence
s are unidentified  deceased or unable to consent to submitting their bodily substance
  or if their 
whereabouts are unknown  their DNA profile may be obtained from 
their remains (if deceased)  
their 
personal ef
fects
  or from any place associated with the commission of the designated offence.
 In a 
situation where a
 body is 
found
 at one site wh
en police know the murder took place at another site
  an 
investigator might request to have the victim\xe2\x84\xa2s DNA profile entered into the VI in an attempt to link the 

body to the crime scene through the NDDB.  
  The 
VDI
 contains DNA profiles from individuals  other than victim
s of designated offence
s  
who 
have 
voluntarily 
provided 
biological samples for the purpose of having their DNA profile added to the index  
where their profile may be relevant to an investigation of a designated offence
  a missing person
  or 
human remains.
 For example  a police officer concer
ned that their
 personal
 profile may be present
 through contamination
 in 
the 
CSI of the NDDB
 may provide their biological sample to have their DNA 
profile entered into the VDI and compared to all other profiles in the NDDB.
   3 VOLUNTARY
 PARTICIPATION 
 Submission of 
a biological sample 
for the VI 
or 
VDI
 is voluntary. 
There is no obligation for a victim of a 
designated offence or for any other individual
 to provide a biological sample
 for the 
development of a 
DNA profile for the NDDB
. The
 NDDB will not 
accept
 a DNA profile 
for inclusion 
into the VI or VDI 
without the proper written consent 
from 
each person donating a sample for submission 
into either of 
these 
indexes
. If 
a victim of 
a designated offence 
cannot be found  
is 
unidentified  
is 
deceased
  or 
is 
otherwise 
unable to consent to submitting 
a biological
 sample
  their DNA profile may be obtained 
by the 
investigator 
from their remains  their personal effects
  or from any place associated with the 
commission of the designated offence.
 '[ PAGE 3 END ][ PAGE 4 START ]  Guide to the Victims Index and Voluntary Donors Index 
of the National DNA Data Bank
 of Canada
   Version 
1.0
 Effective Date: 201
8-03-06 Page 
4 of 
7  Other general co
nsiderations:
  The investigator must assess whether the donor understand
s the purpose for providing 
a biological 
sample
  as well as
 what will be done with that sample and the associated
 DNA profile developed 
from it.
  If the donor is under the age of 18  con
sent 
may
 be provided by a parent/
legal 
guardian. The donor 
will have the opportunity to provide their own consent 
within one year 
after they reach the age of 18 
if they decide to have their DNA profile remain in the 
NDDB.
  Investigators are encouraged to 
read and familiarize themselves with the appropriate consent forms.
  4 SAMPLE COLLECTION AN
D CONSENT
 A criminal 
investigation 
may lead to the submission of
 a DNA profile to the NDDB 
when
 a victim 
of a 
designated offence 
or an individual voluntarily donates their DNA. 
The
 developed 
VI or 
VDI profile will 
be submitted 
to the NDDB 
by 
a public forensic 
laboratory 
that
 has 
authorized access to CODIS
 (Combined DNA Index System
)  the software 
used to retain and 
compare
 DNA profiles
. These 
authorized 
laboratories are
: the 
Centre of Forensic Sciences in Toronto and Sault Ste. Marie
; the 
Laboratoire de 
sciences judiciaires et de m\xc3\xa9decine l\xc3\xa9gale in Montreal
; and the RCMP
\xe2\x84\xa2s
 National Forensic Laboratory 
Services in Vancouver 
 Edmonton and Ottawa. 
 Investigators must collect 
a biological sample 
and
 written 
consent
 for
 each 
voluntary 
donor
. The 
consent may be obtained after the initial analysis of the 
biological 
samples 
by 
the public forensic 
laboratory
  but 
the consent 
must be 
obtained
 before
 any DNA profile from a victim or voluntary donor
 is 
submitted 
to the NDDB
. The consent must be obtained on the form entitled \xef\xac\x81
National DNA Data Bank 
Consent
 to Provide 
Biological S
amples
 \xc5\x92 Consent for a Voluntary Donor
\xef\xac\x82 or 
\xef\xac\x81National DNA Dat
a Bank 
Consent to Provide Biological Samples 
\xc5\x92 Consent for a 
Victim
\xef\xac\x82. Otherwise  the DNA profile derived 
from the 
collected biological 
sample 
will not be accepted 
for entry into the VI or VDI
 by the NDDB
. If 
the 
victim of 
the 
designated offence 
is 
unidentified  deceased
  unable to consent to submitting their bodily 
substance
  or if their whereabouts are unknown  their DNA profile may be obtained from their remains  
their personal effects
  or from any place associated with the commission of the desig
nated offence.
 Circumstances may arise where a DNA profile 
has been previously developed from a victim or volunteer 
donor 
by a public forensic laboratory for a
 criminal investigation
 prior to the 
amendments to the 
DNA 
Identification Act
 and the establishme
nt of 
the 
VI and VDI indexes in the NDDB.
 In such cases
  an existing 
VI or
 VDI 
DNA profile
 can
 be 
entered into
 the 
NDDB 
so long as
 written 
consent
 is obtained from the 
donor
. One of the
 above noted 
consent 
form
s must
 be used.
  5 THE 
PROCESSING 
OF BIOLOGICAL 
SAMPLES
 A biological 
sample collected from 
a victim 
or a 
voluntary donor as part of a criminal investigation 
must 
be sent to 
one of the CODIS participating
 public forensic laborator
ies 
(as 
noted above
) to develop
 the 
DNA profile. These submissions will fol
low the same protocols in place for 
the submission of 
DNA 
profiles derived 
from crime scene
 samples
. The public forensic laborator
ies are
 accredited for this type 
of DNA analysis and 
will make the
 request 
to enter the resulting
 DNA
 profile 
into the VI or V
DI index 
of
 the NDDB
 as 
appropriate
. '[ PAGE 4 END ]

text:
[ PAGE 1 START ]    DNA DATA BANK ADVISORY COMMITTEE RULES OF PROCEDUREInterpretation1. (1) The definitions in this subrule apply in these Rules.Act means the DNA Identification Act.\xef\xac\x81Committee\xef\xac\x82 means the DNA Data Bank Advisory Committee.
\xef\xac\x81Decide\xef\xac\x82 or \xef\xac\x81decision\xef\xac\x82 means any finding or recommendation made by the Committee.intervenor\xef\xac\x82 means a person who is permitted to intervene at a public consultation under rule 17.Participant means any person whom the committee invites as a participant or permits as anintervenor in the proceeding in relation to a matter being considered by the committee in the publicinterest;   \xef\xac\x81RCMP\xef\xac\x82 means the Royal Canadian Mounted Police;  \xef\xac\x81Regulations\xef\xac\x82 means the DNA Data Bank Advisory Committee Regulations;  (2) For greater certainty  document includes information stored by electronic means.PART 1GENERALApplication  Officers and Employees of the RCMP  Quorum2.(1) This Part applies in respect of the following proceedings: (a) an opportunity to be heard as requested by a member or employee of the RCMP;(b) an opportunity to be heard as requested by a public or private agency or a member of thepublic;(c) proceedings conducted by the Committee on its own initiative;'[ PAGE 1 END ][ PAGE 2 START ] (d) a public consultation conducted by the Committee;(2) The Committee may permit or request employees of the RCMP to participate in a proceedingunder these Rules in such manner  including presenting information and submissions orally or in
writing  questioning participants and responding to questions and submissions  as will enable the
Committee to decide the matter in a fair  informal and expeditious manner.(3) For the purposes of proceedings before the Committee under these Rules  the number ofmembers of the Committee that constitutes a quorum shall be five members;Varying Rules3.(1) The Committee may vary or supplement any of these Rules  in order to ensure that a proceeding
be dealt with as informally and expeditiously as the circumstances and the considerations of fairness
permit.(2) Any procedural matter that arises in the course of a proceeding that is not provided for in these
Rules shall be dealt with by the Committee as informally and expeditiously as the circumstances
and the considerations of fairness permit.Defect in Form or Procedure4. No proceeding is invalid  in whole or part  by reason only of a defect in form or failure to follow a
procedure that is set out in these Rules  where the defect or failure does not result in any material harm
to a relevant interest.Waiver of Rules5.(1) Any participant may waive any procedural right that is granted to the participant under these
Rules.(2) In the absence of proof to the contrary  where any participant fails to take advantage of aprocedural right granted under these Rules  the participant is deemed to have waived that right.Time Limits6. Where these Rules indicate that a time limit in to be specified in an order of the Committee or a
notice of the Committee  the time limit specified shall provide for as informal and expeditious a
proceeding as the circumstances and the considerations of fairness permit.Transmitting Documents 7.(1) Unless otherwise provided by these Rules  any giving  sending  notifying  serving or filing that is'[ PAGE 2 END ][ PAGE 3 START ] required or permitted under these Rules may be done(a) by hand  ordinary mail  registered mail or courier;(b) by facsimile  if the recipient is able to receive the information in that manner; or
(c) by any other method that is agreed to by the recipient.
(2) A document that is sent by facsimile must include the following information:(a)  the name  address and telephone and facsimile numbers of the sender;
(b) the date and time of the transmission;
(c) the total number of pages transmitted;
(d) the name  address and telephone and facsimile numbers of the recipient; and
(e) the name  address and telephone and facsimile numbers of a person to contact if transmissionproblems occur.Filing8.(1) Subject to subrule (2)  a document that is required to be filed under these Rules shall be filed at
the office of the Chairperson.(2) During a proceeding  a document may be filed with the presiding member of the Committee who ishearing or considering the matter.(3) In the absence of proof to the contrary  the date of filing is the date on which the document isreceived by the Committee  as indicated(a) by the date stamped on the document by an employee of the office that supports the Committee 
in the case of a document that is filed in accordance with paragraph 7(1)(a); and(b) by the date that appears on the covering page of the facsimile as processed by the receivingfacsimile machine of the Committee  in the case of a document that is filed by facsimile.Official Languages9.(1) Subject to subrule (2)  all documents given to the Committee must be in at least one official
language.'[ PAGE 3 END ][ PAGE 4 START ] (2) A person may give a document in a language other than an official language if  at the same time the person gives a translation of the document in at least one official language  and an affidavit of the
translator attesting to the accuracy of the translation.Confidentiality10 (1) Subject to subrule (2)  in any proceeding  the Committee  as the case may be  may take
measures under subrule (3) to protect information if(a) the information involves national security;(b) the information is confidential information of a financial  commercial  scientific  technical  personal or other nature that is treated consistently as confidentialand the person affected has not consented to the disclosure;  (c) disclosure of the information is likely to endanger the life  liberty or security of a person; or    (d) disclosure of the information may jeopardize an investigation or reveal investigational techniques.  (2) The Committee may take the measures referred to in subrule (3) if    (a) protection of the information outweighs in importance the public interest in public consultationand disclosure of information; and (b) the measures are designed so as not to affect the public nature of the proceeding except to theextent necessary to adequately protect the information.      (3) The measures that the Committee may take include requiring that(a) the proceeding or part of the proceeding take place in private  to the exclusion of members of
the public  other than the participants;(b) the publication of information given to the Committee be restricted or prohibited; and
(c) the disclosure of information given or received by the Committee be prohibited or restricted tosome or all of the participants.Invitations11.(1) In the case of a public consultation that is conducted by the Committee  a participant may
request the Committee to issue an invitation by submitting a request in writing before the start of the
proceeding or an oral request at the proceeding  but in any case as soon as the circumstances giving
rise to the request become known to the participant.'[ PAGE 4 END ]

text:
[ PAGE 1 START ] DNA DATA BANK ADVISORY COMMITTEE BY-LAWSINTERPRETATION1. The definitions in this section apply in these By-laws.Act means the DNA Identification Act.  Chairperson means the Chairperson of the Committee appointed under section 3 of the Regulations.
\xef\xac\x81Committee\xef\xac\x82 means the DNA Data Bank Advisory Committee.
\xef\xac\x81Decision\xef\xac\x82 means any finding or recommendation made by the Committee.
meeting means a meeting of the members of the Committee.
member means a member of the Commission appointed under section 3 of the Regulations. 
\xef\xac\x81RCMP\xef\xac\x82 means the Royal Canadian Mounted Police;
\xef\xac\x81Regulations\xef\xac\x82 means the DNA Data Bank Advisory Committee Regulations made pursuant to the Act.APPLICATION2. These By-laws apply to the management and conduct of the affairs of the Committee and to theprocedures to be followed in proceedings other than those prescribed in the DNA Data BankAdvisory Committee Rules of Procedure.SIGNING OFFICERS3. If the Chairperson is absent or incapacitated or the office of Chairperson is vacant and the
Commissioner has not designated a replacement under section 3 of the Regulations  the Vice-
Chairperson or  in the absence of the Vice-Chairperson a member of the Committee elected by a
quorum of the members present to preside over a meeting  shall sign any decision or other instrument
authorized to be issued or made by the Committee.MEETINGS AND DECISIONS4. Meetings are convened by the Committee or by the Chairperson and are held at any time and place
that the convenor determines.         5. Meetings are held in public or in closed session.'[ PAGE 1 END ][ PAGE 2 START ] 6. Notice of the time and place of a meeting shall be given to each member  and if the meeting is to beheld in public  the notice shall be published in the manner that the Committee determines.7. When urgent matters of business require it  a meeting may be convened without prior notice.
8. If a meeting is to be held in public  the Chairperson shall make the meeting agenda publicly availableat least 30 days before the meeting.9. Failure to give proper or any notice of a meeting does not invalidate the meeting.
10. A meeting may be adjourned from time to time and from place to place  and those in attendanceshall be notified of the time and place the meeting will be reconvened.11. A member who participates at a meeting or in a decision of the Committee is deemed to have votedin the affirmative on any decision or action taken  or resolution or vote passed  unless the member
enters a dissent or an abstention on the record.12. The record of every meeting shall be approved at the next meeting. 
13. If a meeting in held in public  the approved record of the meeting shall be made publicly available in
the manner that the Committee determines.QUORUM14. Quorum for a meeting of the Committee is five members.COMING IN FORCE15. These By-laws come into force on the day on which they are made by the Committee. These By-
laws may be amended at such time and in such manner as determined by the Committee.'[ PAGE 2 END ]

text:
[ PAGE 1 START ] STATUTS DU COMIT\xc3\x89 CONSULTATIF DE LA BANQUE NATIONALE DE DONN\xc3\x89ESG\xc3\x89N\xc3\x89TIQUESD\xc3\x89FINITIONS1. Les d\xc3\xa9finitions qui suivent s\xe2\x84\xa2appliquent aux pr\xc3\xa9sents statuts.\xc2\xabLoi\xc2\xbb La Loi sur l\xe2\x84\xa2identification par les empreintes g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9tiques\xc2\xabpr\xc3\xa9sident\xc2\xbb Le pr\xc3\xa9sident du Comit\xc3\xa9 nomm\xc3\xa9 aux termes de l\xe2\x84\xa2article 3 du R\xc3\xa8glement.
\xc2\xabComit\xc3\xa9\xc2\xbb Le Comit\xc3\xa9 consultatif de la banque nationale de donn\xc3\xa9es g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9tiques
\xc2\xabd\xc3\xa9cision\xc2\xbb Toute conclusion ou recommandation formul\xc3\xa9e par le Comit\xc3\xa9.
\xc2\xabr\xc3\xa9union\xc2\xbb R\xc3\xa9union des membres du Comit\xc3\xa9.
\xc2\xabmembre\xc2\xbb Membre du Comit\xc3\xa9 nomm\xc3\xa9 aux termes de l\xe2\x84\xa2article 3 du R\xc3\xa8glement.
\xc2\xabGRC\xc2\xbb La Gendarmerie royale du Canada.
\xc2\xabR\xc3\xa8glement\xc2\xbb Le R\xc3\xa8glement sur le Comit\xc3\xa9 consultatif de la Banque nationale de donn\xc3\xa9es
g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9tiques pris aux termes de la Loi.CHAMP D\xe2\x84\xa2APPLICATION2. Les pr\xc3\xa9sents statuts portent sur la gestion et la conduite des affaires du Comit\xc3\xa9 et sur les autresproc\xc3\xa9dures \xc3\xa0 suivre que celles pr\xc3\xa9vues dans les R\xc3\xa8gles de proc\xc3\xa9dure du Comit\xc3\xa9 consultatif sur labanque nationale de donn\xc3\xa9es g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9tiques.SIGNATAIRES3. En cas d\xe2\x84\xa2absence ou d\xe2\x84\xa2emp\xc3\xaachement du pr\xc3\xa9sident ou de vacance de son poste et si lecommissaire n\xe2\x84\xa2a pas d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9 de rempla\xc3\xa7ant aux termes de l\xe2\x84\xa2article 3 du R\xc3\xa8glement  le vice-
pr\xc3\xa9sident ou  en l\xe2\x84\xa2absence du vice-pr\xc3\xa9sident  un membre du Comit\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa9lu par quorum des membres
pr\xc3\xa9sents pour pr\xc3\xa9sider la r\xc3\xa9union  signe toute d\xc3\xa9cision que le comit\xc3\xa9 est autoris\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 prendre ou tout
document qu\xe2\x84\xa2il est autoris\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 faire.R\xc3\x89UNIONS ET D\xc3\x89CISIONS4. Le Comit\xc3\xa9 ou le pr\xc3\xa9sident convoque les r\xc3\xa9unions et en fixe la date  l\xe2\x84\xa2heure et le lieu.5. Les r\xc3\xa9unions sont ouvertes au public ou se tiennent \xc3\xa0 huis clos.
6. Un pr\xc3\xa9avis de la date  de l\xe2\x84\xa2heure et du lieu de la r\xc3\xa9union est donn\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 chaque membre et si lar\xc3\xa9union est ouverte au public  le pr\xc3\xa9avis est publi\xc3\xa9 de la mani\xc3\xa8re que d\xc3\xa9termine le Comit\xc3\xa9.7.  En cas d\xe2\x84\xa2urgence  une r\xc3\xa9union peut \xc3\xaatre convoqu\xc3\xa9e sans pr\xc3\xa9avis.
8. Si une r\xc3\xa9union est ouverte au public  le pr\xc3\xa9sident rend public l\xe2\x84\xa2ordre du jour au moins trentejours avant la tenue de la r\xc3\xa9union.9. Aucune erreur ni omission relative \xc3\xa0 l\xe2\x84\xa2avis de convocation d\xe2\x84\xa2une r\xc3\xa9union n\xe2\x84\xa2invalide cette'[ PAGE 1 END ][ PAGE 2 START ] r\xc3\xa9union.10. Une r\xc3\xa9union peut \xc3\xaatre ajourn\xc3\xa9e en tout temps et en tout lieu  auquel cas les membres pr\xc3\xa9sentssont avis\xc3\xa9s de la date  de l\xe2\x84\xa2heure et du lieu de sa reprise.11. Le membre qui participe \xc3\xa0 une r\xc3\xa9union ou une d\xc3\xa9cision du Comit\xc3\xa9 est r\xc3\xa9put\xc3\xa9 avoir donn\xc3\xa9 unvote affirmatif sur toute d\xc3\xa9cision ou mesure prise  ou r\xc3\xa9solution ou vote adopt\xc3\xa9  \xc3\xa0 moins qu\xe2\x84\xa2il ne
consigne sa dissidence ou son abstention au proc\xc3\xa8s-verbal.12. Le proc\xc3\xa8s-verbal de chaque r\xc3\xa9union est approuv\xc3\xa9 lors de la r\xc3\xa9union suivante.
13. Si la r\xc3\xa9union est ouverte au public  le proc\xc3\xa8s-verbal approuv\xc3\xa9 de la r\xc3\xa9union est distribu\xc3\xa9 de lamani\xc3\xa8re que d\xc3\xa9termine le Comit\xc3\xa9.QUORUM14. Le quorum \xc3\xa0 une r\xc3\xa9union est constitu\xc3\xa9 par cinq membres.ENTR\xc3\x89E EN VIGUEUR15. Les pr\xc3\xa9sents statuts entrent en vigueur \xc3\xa0 la date de leur adoption par le Comit\xc3\xa9. Ils peuvent\xc3\xaatre modifi\xc3\xa9s de la mani\xc3\xa8re et au moment que d\xc3\xa9termine le Comit\xc3\xa9.'[ PAGE 2 END ]

. 2 CONTEXTE
 La 
GRC
 est le gestionnaire de
 la Banque nationale de donn\xc3\xa9es g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9tiques
 (BNDG
) pour le compte
 du
 gouvernement
 du
 Canada
. Celle
-ci exerce ses activit\xc3\xa9s \xc3\xa0 l\xe2\x84\xa2intention
 de l\xe2\x84\xa2e
nsemble
 des services
 de police 
du
 Canada. 
En 2014  le gouvernement
 du
 Canada 
a modifi\xc3\xa9 la
 Loi sur
 l\xe2\x84\xa2i
dentification 
par les empreintes 
g\xc3\xa9n\xc3\xa9tiques
 pour 
cr\xc3\xa9er
 cinq 
nouveaux fichiers 
de profils d\xe2\x84\xa2ADN
 \xc3\xa0 la BNDG
 : le fichier des
 victimes
 (FV)  
le 
fichier 
des donneurs v
olontai
res
 (FDV)  
le fichier des
 personne
s disparues
 (FPD
)  
le fichier des restes 
humain
s (FRH
) et le fichier des
 parents de 
personne
s disparues
 (fichier des familles des personnes 
disparues 
FFPD). Les 
FPD
  
FRH
 et FFPD ont \xc3\xa9t\xc3\xa9
 constitu\xc3\xa9s
 \xc3\xa0 des
 fins
 humanitaires
 pour 
enqu\xc3\xaater sur des

 disparues

 humain
s (consulter le
 Guide 
de l\xe2\x84\xa2enqu\xc3\xaateur 
sur 
le 
Programme national 
d\xe2\x84\xa2ADN pour les personnes 
disparues
). Le 
FV peut 
servir
 aux enqu\xc3\xaate
s sur des
 infractions criminelles 
d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9es
  et le FDV
 pe
ut \xc3\xaatre utile aux
 enqu\xc3\xaate
s de nature 
criminel
le et 
humanitaire
.  Le 
FV
 conti
ent des
 profil
s d\xe2\x84\xa2ADN
 \xc3\xa9tablis \xc3\xa0 partir d
\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9chantillons

fournis 
volontai
rement 
par 
de
s victimes

s. Si les

infraction

es

ir \xc3\xa0 soumettre un \xc3\xa9chantillon de

s corporelle
s  ou

 peut \xc3\xaatre

 de
 leur
s restes
 (si elles sont 
d\xc3\xa9c\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9es
)  
de l
eur
s effets
 personne
ls  ou 
de

 associ
\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 l\xe2\x84\xa2accomplissement
 de
 l\xe2\x84\xa2infraction 
d\xc3\xa9sign\xc3\xa9e
. Dans le cas o\xc3\xb9 un corps

\xc3\xa0 un endroit
 alors
 que les

 savent que le meurtre

  un

 peut demander 
que le

 de la victime soit ajout\xc3\xa9 au

de 
tenter de

 une concordance avec

Le 
FDV
 conti
ent des 
profil
s d\xe2\x84\xa2ADN
 \xc3\xa9tablis \xc3\xa0 partir d

biologiques 
fournis

rement par 
de
s personnes

s

 leur

 peut \xc3\xaatre 
utile

 une

  une

 ou

s. Par

ns le

text:
[ PAGE 1 START ] ContexteCertaines drogues  notamment le cannabis  peuvent 
nuire \xc3\xa0 votre capacit\xc3\xa9 de conduire et augmenter 

le risque de collision. Au Canada  le nombre de 

conducteurs d\xc3\xa9c\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9s dans des accidents de la route 

dont le test de d\xc3\xa9pistage de drogue donne des r\xc3\xa9sultats 

positifs d\xc3\xa9passe celui des conducteurs dont les r\xc3\xa9sultats 

au test de d\xc3\xa9pistage d\xe2\x84\xa2alcool \xc3\xa9taient positifs. Les jeunes 

continuent par ailleurs de former le groupe le plus 

important de conducteurs qui  apr\xc3\xa8s avoir perdu la vie 

dans une collision  re\xc3\xa7oivent des r\xc3\xa9sultats positifs \xc3\xa0 

l\xe2\x84\xa2analyse visant \xc3\xa0 d\xc3\xa9celer la pr\xc3\xa9sence d\xe2\x84\xa2alcool et/ou de 

drogue dans l\xe2\x84\xa2organisme.
Saviez-vous que la conduite avec facult\xc3\xa9s affaiblies est l'une des principales causes criminelles de d\xc3\xa9c\xc3\xa8s et de blessures au Canada?
Cette ressource fournit de l\xe2\x84\xa2information sur les 
e\xcb\x9aets des drogues sur la capacit\xc3\xa9 de conduire 

d\xe2\x84\xa2une personne. Parlez-en avec les jeunes et aidez-

les \xc3\xa0 prendre des d\xc3\xa9cisions \xc3\xa9clair\xc3\xa9es sur leur 

comportement au volant.
Conduite avec facult\xc3\xa9s  affaiblies par la drogue
Les e\xcb\x9aets des drogues (l\xc3\xa9gales  ill\xc3\xa9gales ou sur ordon
-
nance) peuvent se faire sentir de nombreuses fa\xc3\xa7ons. 

M\xc3\xaame de petites quantit\xc3\xa9s peuvent augmenter le 
risque d\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xaatre victime d\xe2\x84\xa2une collision impliquant des 

v\xc3\xa9hicules \xc3\xa0 moteur. Di\xcb\x9a\xc3\xa9rentes drogues ont des e\xcb\x9aets 

di\xcb\x9a\xc3\xa9rents sur le cerveau et le corps et peuvent nuire  \xc3\xa0 

la capacit\xc3\xa9 de conduire. Les drogues peuvent notam
-
ment causer les e\xcb\x9aets suivants :
 \xcb\x9bTemps de r\xc3\xa9action diminu\xc3\xa9 ou augment\xc3\xa9
 \xcb\x9bSomnolence
 \xcb\x9bCapacit\xc3\xa9 r\xc3\xa9duite de faire face \xc3\xa0 des 
 \xc3\xa9v\xc3\xa9nements inattendus
 \xcb\x9bAtteinte \xc3\xa0 la m\xc3\xa9moire \xc3\xa0 court terme
 \xcb\x9bConcentration d\xc3\xa9\xcb\x86ciente
 \xcb\x9bCapacit\xc3\xa9 r\xc3\xa9duite de diviser l\xe2\x84\xa2attention
 \xcb\x9bCapacit\xc3\xa9 r\xc3\xa9duite de percevoir le temps et l\xe2\x84\xa2espace
 \xcb\x9bIncidence n\xc3\xa9gative sur le jugement et la capacit\xc3\xa9 
 de prendre des d\xc3\xa9cisions
 \xcb\x9bAugmentation des comportements \xc3\xa0 risque
 \xcb\x9bTroubles de l\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9quilibre et de la coordination
Voici sept cat\xc3\xa9gories de drogues qui peuvent nuire \xc3\xa0 

la capacit\xc3\xa9 de conduire des personnes et certains de 

leurs e\xcb\x9aets potentiels :
D\xc3\xa9presseurs du syst\xc3\xa8me nerveux central
p. ex.  Xanax  Ativan  E\xcb\x9cexor  Paxil  Valium
Les d\xc3\xa9presseurs du syst\xc3\xa8me nerveux central ralentissent 
l\xe2\x84\xa2activit\xc3\xa9 c\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9brale  provoquent de la somnolence et 

peuvent causer des troubles de l\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9locution. Ils peuvent 

\xc3\xa9galement causer un manque de 

coordination et un ralentissement 

des mouvements.  
Hallucinog\xc3\xa8nes p. ex.  LSD  ecstasy  mescaline  psilocybine
Les hallucinog\xc3\xa8nes peuvent d\xc3\xa9former les messages 
sensoriels transmis au cerveau - ils peuvent alt\xc3\xa9rer 

le go\xc3\xbbt  la vue  l\xe2\x84\xa2ou\xc3\xafe  l\xe2\x84\xa2odorat et les sensations. Ces 
drogues peuvent nuire \xc3\xa0 la prise de d\xc3\xa9cisions  \xc3\xa0 la 
m\xc3\xa9moire  \xc3\xa0 la perception et \xc3\xa0 la capacit\xc3\xa9 de contr\xc3\xb4ler la 

vitesse et de s\xe2\x84\xa2adapter au changement.
Stimulants du syst\xc3\xa8me nerveux centralp. ex.  coca\xc3\xafne  m\xc3\xa9thamph\xc3\xa9tamine  cristaux de 

m\xc3\xa9thamph\xc3\xa9tamine  amph\xc3\xa9tamine (speed)  Ritalin 
Les stimulants acc\xc3\xa9l\xc3\xa8rent et stimulent l\xe2\x84\xa2activit\xc3\xa9 c\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9brale 
et le fonctionnement du corps. Cela peut entra\xc3\xaener une 

incapacit\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 se concentrer ou \xc3\xa0 diviser son attention  et 

augmenter les comportements \xc3\xa0 risque. 
Analg\xc3\xa9siques narcotiques 
p. ex.  oxycodone  fentanyl  h\xc3\xa9ro\xc3\xafne  m\xc3\xa9thadone  cod\xc3\xa9ine 
Un conducteur sous l\xe2\x84\xa2e\xcb\x9aet d\xe2\x84\xa2analg\xc3\xa9siques narcotiques 
peut \xc3\xaatre somnolent  conduire plus lentement et/

ou en zigzag  avoir les pupilles contract\xc3\xa9es  respirer 

lentement  avoir une mauvaise ma\xc3\xaetrise du v\xc3\xa9hicule et 

des r\xc3\xa9actions tardives.    
Cannabis/Marijuanap. ex.  haschich  huile de haschich  shatter  budder  
 
cire  dabs  kif  produits comestibles  teinture  cr\xc3\xa8mes  pot 
La consommation de cannabis a des e\xcb\x9aets sur les 
capacit\xc3\xa9s cognitives et motrices. Cela peut entra\xc3\xaener 

une capacit\xc3\xa9 r\xc3\xa9duite de diviser son attention et de 

percevoir le temps et l\xe2\x84\xa2espace  de la fatigue  du stress 
et une di\xcb\x9dcult\xc3\xa9 \xc3\xa0 se concentrer. Les e\xcb\x9aets du cannabis 

d\xc3\xa9pendent de plusieurs facteurs  tels que le type et la 

quantit\xc3\xa9 de cannabis consomm\xc3\xa9 et la fa\xc3\xa7on dont le 

cannabis est ing\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9.
Anesth\xc3\xa9siques dissociatifsp. ex.  PCP  k\xc3\xa9tamine  dextrom\xc3\xa9thorphane (DXM)
Les anesth\xc3\xa9siques dissociatifs peuvent causer 
des comportements cycliques de non-r\xc3\xa9ceptivit\xc3\xa9  

des hallucinations et une augmentation de la 

temp\xc3\xa9rature corporelle.    
Inhalantsp. ex.  essence  whippits  d\xc3\xa9poussi\xc3\xa9reur \xc3\xa0 air pour 

ordinateur  oxyde de diazote  autres solvants volatils
Les inhalants peuvent causer une rougeur dans les yeux  
une grande confusion  des rougeurs au visage  une tr\xc3\xa8s 

mauvaise coordination et une intoxication grave. En cas 

d\xe2\x84\xa2utilisation prolong\xc3\xa9e  ils peuvent \xc3\xa9galement causer 

des l\xc3\xa9sions c\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9brales permanentes.    
La conduite avec facult\xc3\xa9s  affaiblies et la loiLa conduite avec facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies  qu\xe2\x84\xa2elle soit at
-tribuable \xc3\xa0 de la drogue (m\xc3\xaame des m\xc3\xa9dicaments pre
-
scrits par un m\xc3\xa9decin)  \xc3\xa0 de l\xe2\x84\xa2alcool ou \xc3\xa0 l\xe2\x84\xa2e\xcb\x9aet combin\xc3\xa9 

des deux  est ill\xc3\xa9gale et peut entra\xc3\xaener une infraction 

criminelle en vertu du 
Code criminel
. Il est interdit par 
la loi de conduire un v\xc3\xa9hicule \xc3\xa0 moteur en ayant les 

facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies  y compris des v\xc3\xa9hicules  des bateaux  

des v\xc3\xa9hicules tout terrain (VTT)  des motoneiges et des 

scooters (essence ou \xc3\xa9lectrique).
Les policiers sont form\xc3\xa9s pour d\xc3\xa9tecter les 
conducteurs aux facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies par la drogue en 
\xc2\xa9 Sa Majest\xc3\xa9 la Reine du chef du Canada  repr\xc3\xa9sent\xc3\xa9e par la 
Gendarmerie royale du Canada  2019.
No de catalogue PS64-136/2016  |  ISBN: 978-0-660-06079-8
utilisant sur place des tests de sobri\xc3\xa9t\xc3\xa9 normalis\xc3\xa9s 
(TSN) et en soumettant les conducteurs \xc3\xa0 une 

\xc3\xa9valuation par un expert en reconnaissance des 

drogues (ERD). Ils peuvent \xc3\xa9galement demander 

un \xc3\xa9chantillon de sang  d\xe2\x84\xa2urine ou de salive pour la 

d\xc3\xa9tection de substances psychoactives.
Dans les cas o\xc3\xb9 il y a conduite avec facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies  
en plus des sanctions p\xc3\xa9nales  plusieurs provinces et 

territoires imposent des sanctions administratives. 

Celles-ci peuvent comprendre des amendes  la 

suspension du permis de conduire et des programmes 

d\xe2\x84\xa2\xc3\xa9ducation et de d\xc3\xa9judiciarisation. Consultez la 

l\xc3\xa9gislation provinciale ou territoriale pour obtenir de 

plus amples renseignements sur les cons\xc3\xa9quences de la 

conduite avec les facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies dans votre r\xc3\xa9gion. 
Pr\xc3\xa9ventionPour aider les jeunes \xc3\xa0 faire des choix \xc3\xa9clair\xc3\xa9s et 

r\xc3\xa9duire les risques associ\xc3\xa9s \xc3\xa0 la conduite avec facult\xc3\xa9s 

a\xcb\x9aaiblies par la drogue :
 \xcb\x9bSoyez un mod\xc3\xa8le positif;
 \xcb\x9bConnaissez les faits. Les jeunes font leur propre 

recherche  surtout en ligne  et ce qu\xe2\x84\xa2ils trouvent 

n\xe2\x84\xa2est pas toujours exact;
 \xcb\x9bParlez avec franchise des m\xc3\xa9faits  des 

cons\xc3\xa9quences et des dangers de la conduite avec 

facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies par la drogue;
 \xcb\x9bFournissez aux jeunes des solutions de rechange 

pour \xc3\xa9viter qu\xe2\x84\xa2ils conduisent avec les facult\xc3\xa9s 

a\xcb\x9aaiblies ou qu\xe2\x84\xa2ils montent \xc3\xa0 bord d\xe2\x84\xa2un v\xc3\xa9hicule 
dont le conducteur a les facult\xc3\xa9s a\xcb\x9aaiblies. Par 

exemple : 
 \xc2\xbbd\xc3\xa9signer un conducteur;
 \xc2\xbbutiliser un autre moyen de transport 

(autobus  taxi  ami ou membre de la 

famille);
 \xc2\xbbpasser la nuit sur place si c\xe2\x84\xa2est possible et 

s\xc3\xa9curitaire de la faire.
 \xcb\x9bEncouragez activement les jeunes \xc3\xa0 rester sobres 

lorsqu\xe2\x84\xa2ils prennent le volant et \xc3\xa0 faire des choix 

sains qui leur permettront d\xe2\x84\xa2atteindre leurs 

objectifs personnels.

text:
[ PAGE 1 START ] Background
Some drugs  including cannabis  can impair your 
ability to drive and increase the risk of collisions. 

In Canada  the number of drivers killed in motor 

vehicle crashes who test positive for drugs exceeds 

the number of drivers who test positive for alcohol. 

Young people continue to be the largest group of 

drivers who die in crashes and later test positive 
 
for alcohol and/or drugs.
Did you know that impaired driving 
 is a leading criminal cause of death  and injury in Canada?\xcb\x9cis resource provides information about the 
 
e\xcb\x9aects of drugs on a person\xe2\x84\xa2s ability to drive. Have 
 
the conversation with young people and support 

them in making informed decisions about their 

driving behaviour.
Drug-Impaired Driving
Drugs (legal  illegal or prescription) can a\xcb\x9aect us 

in many ways. Even small amounts can increase 

your chances of being involved in a motor vehicle 

collision. Di\xcb\x9aerent drugs have di\xcb\x9aerent e\xcb\x9aects on 
your brain and body  and can impair the ability to 

drive by:
 \xcb\x9bSlowing or increasing reaction time
 \xcb\x9bIncreasing sleepiness
 \xcb\x9bReducing the ability to handle unexpected events
 \xcb\x9bImpairing short-term memory
 \xcb\x9bImpairing concentration
 \xcb\x9bReducing the ability to divide attention
 \xcb\x9bCausing a poor time and space perception
 \xcb\x9bImpairing judgment and decision-making
 \xcb\x9bIncreasing risk-taking behaviour
 \xcb\x9bImpairing balance and coordination
Here are seven categories of drugs which can 

impair drivers and some of their potential e\xcb\x9aects:
Central nervous system depressants
e.g.  Xanax  Ativan  E\xcb\x9cexor  Paxil  Valium
Central nervous system depressants slow down 
 brain activity  cause drowsiness and can cause 
 
slurred speech. \xcb\x9cey can also cause slow 

uncoordinated movements.   
Hallucinogens e.g.  LSD  ecstasy  mescaline  psilocybin
Hallucinogens can distort sensory messages to the 
brain\xc5\xa0they can alter taste  sight  hearing  smell 

and feeling. \xcb\x9cese drugs can impair decision-

making  memory  perception and the ability to 

control speed and adapt to change.
Central nervous system stimulantse.g.  cocaine  meth  crystal meth  speed  Ritalin 
Stimulants accelerate and excite the brain and the 
body. \xcb\x9cis may result in the inability to focus and 

divide attention  and an increase in risk-taking.
Narcotic analgesics 
e.g.  oxycodone  fentanyl  heroin  methadone  codeine 
A driver under the e\xcb\x9aects of narcotic analgesics 
may be drowsy  drive slower  have pinpoint pupils  

breathe slowly  weave in and out of lanes  have 

poor vehicle control and delayed reaction times.
Cannabis/Marijuanae.g.  hashish  cannabis oil  hash oil  shatter  budder  

wax  dabs  kief  edibles  tinctures  creams  pot 
Cannabis use a\xcb\x9aects cognitive and motor abilities. 
\xcb\x9cis can result in a reduced ability to divide 

attention  fatigue  stress  poor time and space 

perception  and di\xcb\x9dculty concentrating. \xcb\x9ce 

e\xcb\x9aects of cannabis depend on several factors  such 
as the type of cannabis used  how the cannabis is 

ingested and how much a person takes.
Dissociative anestheticse.g.  PCP  ketamine  dextromethorphan (DXM)
Dissociative anesthetics can cause cyclic 
unresponsive behaviours  hallucinations and an 

increased body temperature.  
Inhalantse.g.  gasoline  whippits  computer air duster  nitrous 

oxide  other volatile solvents
Inhalants can cause bloodshot eyes  severe 
confusion  \xcb\x99ushed face  extremely poor 

coordination and severe intoxication. With 

prolonged use  they can also cause permanent 

brain damage.  
Impaired Driving and the Law
Impaired driving  whether caused by drugs (even if 

prescribed by a doctor)  alcohol or a combination 

of both  is illegal and can result in a criminal 

o\xcb\x9aence under the 
Criminal Code of Canada
. It\xe2\x84\xa2s 
illegal to operate any type of motor vehicles while 

impaired  including cars  boats  all-terrain vehicles 

(ATV)  snowmobiles  and scooters (gas or electric).
Police o\xcb\x9dcers are trained to detect drug-impaired 
driving using roadside Standard Field Sobriety 
\xc2\xa9 Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Canada  as 
represented by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police  2019.

Cat. No.: PS64-136/2016  |  ISBN: 978-0-660-06079-8
Testing (SFST) and Drug Recognition Expert 
(DRE) evaluations. \xcb\x9cey can also demand a 

sample of blood  urine  or oral \xcb\x99uid to test for the 

presence of impairing substances.
In addition to criminal penalties  many provinces 
and territories impose administrative sanctions 

for impaired driving. \xcb\x9cese may include \xcb\x86nes  

licence suspensions  and education or diversion 

programs. Check your provincial or territorial 

laws for information on the consequences of 

impaired driving in your area.
Prevention
To help young people make informed choices 
 
and reduce the risks associated with drug-

impaired driving:
 \xcb\x9bBe a positive role model;
 \xcb\x9bKnow the facts! Young people are doing their 

own research  especially online\xc5\xa0not all of 

what they \xcb\x86nd is true;
 \xcb\x9bTalk with youth openly and honestly about 
 
the harms  consequences and dangers of 
 
drug-impaired driving;
 \xcb\x9bProvide youth with alternatives to driving 

impaired or getting in the car with someone who 

is. For example: 
 \xc2\xbbDesignate a driver;
 \xc2\xbbUse alternative modes of transportation 

(public transportation  taxi  friend or 

family member);
 \xc2\xbbStay the night if possible and safe to do so.
 \xcb\x9bActively encourage youth to drive sober and to 

make healthy life choices that will enable them to 

reach their personal goals.
For More Information
